## 3. GET vs POST for List Endpoints

| Endpoint type | Method | When |
|---------------|--------|------|
| Simple list (no filters) | `GET` | Accounts, channels — use `params` for pagination |
| Filtered list | `POST` | Campaigns, keywords, targets — send `{ filters }` in body |
| Detail | `GET` | Single entity by ID |
| Create/Update/Delete | `POST`/`PATCH`/`DELETE` | Standard |

```ts
// Simple list — GET
const { data } = await api.get("/accounts/", { params: { page: 1, page_size: 10 } });

// Filtered list — POST (backend expects filters in body)
const { data } = await api.post(url, { filters: { campaign_name__icontains: "test" } });
```

---

## 4. Response Formats

| Type | Shape |
|------|-------|
| Paginated (DRF) | `{ count, next, previous, results }` |
| Custom list | `{ campaigns: [...] }` or `{ keywords: [...] }` |
| Create/update | Entity object `{ id, name, ... }` |
| Error | `{ error: string }` or `{ detail: string }` |

Handle both shapes:
```ts
const list = Array.isArray(data) ? data : (data?.results ?? data?.campaigns ?? []);
```

### Error Handling
```ts
try {
  const result = await myEntityService.create(payload);
} catch (err: any) {
  const msg = err.response?.data?.error ?? err.response?.data?.detail ?? "Request failed";
  setError(msg);
}
```

